#
# WHAT IS cosmiconfig AND WHY IS IT THE 65TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# cosmiconfig (https://github.com/cosmiconfig/cosmiconfig, 4,151+
# stars) is **David Clark's library for finding and loading
# configuration from a package.json property, rc file, TypeScript
# module, and more!** — the dominant Node.js library for CONFIG-
# FILE DISCOVERY.  Where Rust config-rs (R629) and Go viper (R630)
# load explicitly-specified config files, cosmiconfig SEARCHES for
# the config file in a hierarchy of standard locations by walking
# UP from cwd to the filesystem root.
#
# cosmiconfig's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. SEARCH-PLACES PATTERN — cosmiconfig's central feature is the
#      searchPlaces array, ordered by priority within each directory:
#
#          import { cosmiconfig } from 'cosmiconfig';
#
#          const explorer = cosmiconfig('myapp', {
#              searchPlaces: [
#                  'package.json',         // first: package.json
#                                          //  "myapp" key
#                  '.myapprc',             // RC file (JSON/YAML
#                                          //  auto-detected)
#                  '.myapprc.json',
#                  '.myapprc.yaml',
#                  '.myapprc.yml',
#                  '.myapprc.js',
#                  '.myapprc.cjs',
#                  '.myapprc.mjs',
#                  'myapp.config.js',
#                  'myapp.config.cjs',
#                  'myapp.config.mjs',
#              ],
#          });
#
#          const result = await explorer.search();
#          // result = { config: {...}, filepath: '/path/to/file',
#          //            isEmpty: false } OR null if not found
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust config-rs (R629): explicit File::with_name calls
#         * Go viper (R630): viper.AddConfigPath + SetConfigName
#                              (similar concept, less ergonomic)
#         * Node node-config: NODE_ENV-based file naming
#         * Node conf (Sindre Sorhus): fixed location only
#         * Node dotenv: .env only
#         * cosmiconfig: SEARCH-PLACES ARRAY with auto-format
#                         detection from extension
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 13 library with searchPlaces-
#      array-based discovery semantics.
#
#   2. UPWARD DIRECTORY WALKING — cosmiconfig walks from cwd UP the
#      directory tree to the filesystem root (or to the user's home
#      directory via the stopDir option), looking for the first
#      config file in any of the searchPlaces:
#
#          // Search starting from /home/user/project/src/lib/:
#          await explorer.search();
#
#          // cosmiconfig tries each searchPlace in:
#          //   /home/user/project/src/lib/.myapprc
#          //   /home/user/project/src/lib/package.json (key)
#          //   /home/user/project/src/.myapprc
#          //   /home/user/project/src/package.json (key)
#          //   /home/user/project/.myapprc
#          //   /home/user/project/package.json (key)
#          //   /home/user/.myapprc
#          //   /home/user/package.json (key)
#          //   ... (up to stopDir or filesystem root)
#
#      This matches how `git config` finds .git/config + how npm
#      resolves package.json + how Node module resolution works.
#      Compare:
#         * Rust config-rs (R629): no upward walking
#         * Go viper (R630): viper.AddConfigPath checks each
#                              listed directory separately, no
#                              walking
#         * cosmiconfig: AUTOMATIC upward walking with stopDir
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 13 library with automatic
#      upward-directory-walking config discovery.
#
#   3. PACKAGE.JSON KEY DISCOVERY — cosmiconfig's FIRST search-
#      place by default is a key in package.json — matching the
#      dominant Node convention for tool configuration:
#
#          // package.json:
#          {
#              "name": "my-project",
#              "scripts": { ... },
#              "eslintConfig": { ... },   // ← found by cosmiconfig
#                                          //   when searching for
#                                          //   "eslint"
#              "browserslist": [ ... ],   // ← found by cosmiconfig
#                                          //   for "browserslist"
#              "prettier": { ... },       // ← found by cosmiconfig
#                                          //   for "prettier"
#          }
#
#      This is why so many Node tools (ESLint, Prettier, Babel,
#      Stylelint, Browserslist) accept config in package.json
#      keys — they all use cosmiconfig (or compatible discovery).
#      Compare:
#         * Rust config-rs (R629): no Cargo.toml key search
#         * Go viper (R630): no go.mod key search
#         * cosmiconfig: package.json KEY is FIRST searchPlace
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 13 library with package.json-
#      key as a first-class discovery mechanism.
#
#   4. PLUGGABLE LOADERS via loaders option — cosmiconfig supports
#      arbitrary file extensions via pluggable loader functions:
#
#          import { cosmiconfig } from 'cosmiconfig';
#          import tsLoader from 'cosmiconfig-typescript-loader';
#          import tomlLoader from '@iarna/toml';
#
#          const explorer = cosmiconfig('myapp', {
#              searchPlaces: [
#                  'myapp.config.ts',
#                  'myapp.config.toml',
#                  'myapp.config.js',
#              ],
#              loaders: {
#                  '.ts': tsLoader(),
#                  '.toml': (filepath, content) =>
#                      tomlLoader.parse(content),
#                  '.js': defaultLoaders['.js'],  // built-in
#              },
#          });
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust config-rs (R629): 7 built-in formats + Format
#                                    trait for custom
#         * Go viper (R630): 7+ built-in formats + RegisterFormat
#         * cosmiconfig: PLUGGABLE LOADERS via extension-keyed map
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 13 library with extension-
#      keyed pluggable loader map.
#
#   5. DAVID CLARK / ESLINT-PRETTIER-STYLELINT FOUNDATIONAL
#      PROVENANCE — cosmiconfig is by David Clark (davidtheclark
#      on GitHub) since 2015, now community-maintained under the
#      cosmiconfig org.  cosmiconfig is the discovery layer
#      beneath:
#         * ESLint (130k+ stars) — uses cosmiconfig internally
#         * Prettier (50k+ stars) — uses cosmiconfig
#         * Stylelint — uses cosmiconfig
#         * Babel — uses cosmiconfig for babel.config.* discovery
#         * Browserslist — uses cosmiconfig (lookup in package
#                            .json "browserslist" key)
#         * lint-staged — uses cosmiconfig
#         * Husky — uses cosmiconfig
#         * commitlint — uses cosmiconfig
#         * semantic-release — uses cosmiconfig
#         * postcss — uses cosmiconfig
#         * webpack (some plugins)
#         * Vite + Rollup plugins
#         * craco (THIS — Create React App config override)
#         * react-native-community/cli (RN tooling)
#         * Sequelize CLI
#         * Mojang/minecraft-scripting-libraries
#         * thousands of Node.js dev tools
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 13 library with this specific
#      David-Clark + ESLint/Prettier/Stylelint foundational
#      provenance.
#
# cosmiconfig's relationship to other Axis 13 libraries:
#
#   * Unlike config-rs (R629, Rust) — config-rs is builder pattern
#                                       with serde + 7 file formats;
#                                       cosmiconfig is search-places
#                                       upward walk
#   * Unlike viper (R630, Go) — viper is global singleton with
#                                 pflag/cobra integration; cosmiconfig
#                                 is file-discovery library + per-
#                                 instance explorer
#   * Closest analogs in Node:
#         * conf (Sindre Sorhus) — fixed-location persistent
#                                    config (narrower)
#         * node-config — NODE_ENV-based hierarchical
#         * dotenv — .env file loading only
#         * rc — runtime configuration loader
#         * lilconfig — drop-in cosmiconfig replacement
#                         (smaller dependency)
#     cosmiconfig is the FIRST documented Node.js Axis 13 library
#     providing search-places + upward walking + package.json key
#     discovery + pluggable loaders + sync/async APIs + ESLint/
#     Prettier/Stylelint foundational role.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE craco CLI — minimal dispatch + cosmiconfig + cross-spawn + react-scripts wrap
#
# craco's CLI is in packages/craco/src/bin/craco.ts.  Minimal
# subcommand dispatch:
#
#     #!/usr/bin/env node
#     import spawn from 'cross-spawn';
#
#     const args = process.argv.slice(2);
#     const scriptIndex = args.findIndex(
#         (x) => x === 'build' || x === 'start' || x === 'test'
#     );
#     const script = scriptIndex === -1 ? args[0] : args[scriptIndex];
#
#     switch (script) {
#         case 'build':
#         case 'start':
#         case 'test': {
#             const nodeArgs = scriptIndex > 0 ? args.slice(0, scriptIndex) : [];
#             const scriptPath = require.resolve(`../scripts/${script}`);
#             const scriptArgs = args.slice(scriptIndex + 1);
#             const processArgs = nodeArgs.concat(scriptPath).concat(scriptArgs);
#             const child = spawn.sync('node', processArgs,
#                                        { stdio: 'inherit' });
#             ...
#         }
#         default:
#             console.log(`Unknown script "${script}".`);
#     }
#
# Config discovery via cosmiconfig (packages/craco/src/lib/config.ts):
#
#     import { cosmiconfigSync } from 'cosmiconfig';
#     import tsLoader from 'cosmiconfig-typescript-loader';
#
#     const explorer = cosmiconfigSync('craco', {
#         searchPlaces: [
#             'package.json',         // "craco" key
#             'craco.config.ts',
#             'craco.config.js',
#             'craco.config.cjs',
#             '.cracorc.ts',
#             '.cracorc.js',
#             '.cracorc',
#         ],
#         loaders: {
#             '.ts': tsLoader(),
#         },
#     });
#
# Two craco-specific flags (args.ts):
#     --verbose          Log every config-override application
#     --config <path>    Override auto-discovered config path
#
# Subcommands:
#     craco build [react-scripts args...]
#     craco start [react-scripts args...]
#     craco test  [react-scripts args...]
#
# All other args are PASSED THROUGH to react-scripts.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from config-rs (R629) and viper (R630):
#
#   1. SEARCH-PLACES PATTERN — cosmiconfig's central feature;
#      neither config-rs nor viper have it.
#
#   2. UPWARD DIRECTORY WALKING — cosmiconfig auto-walks from
#      cwd to filesystem root; config-rs/viper require explicit
#      paths.
#
#   3. PACKAGE.JSON KEY DISCOVERY — cosmiconfig's first
#      searchPlace; unique to Node.js convention.
#
#   4. PLUGGABLE EXTENSION-KEYED LOADERS — cosmiconfig has
#      extension-to-loader map; config-rs uses Format trait;
#      viper uses RegisterFormat.
#
#   5. DAVID-CLARK / ESLINT-PRETTIER-FOUNDATIONAL — cosmiconfig
#      underlies the entire Node.js dev-tool layer (ESLint,
#      Prettier, Stylelint, Babel, Browserslist, etc.).
#
